      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Reproductive Rights'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elsie P Palmer letter says many countries resent Americans who push for 'reproductive rights,' meaning abortion (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One hears much about ''reproductive rights'' (letter, May 8). To the uninitiated, the phrase would probably mean the right to reproduce. But when used by the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy and other groups, it means the right not to reproduce, but to abort one's child.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One hears much about ''reproductive rights'' (letter, May 8). To the uninitiated, the phrase would probably mean the right to reproduce. But when used by the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy and other groups, it means the right not to reproduce, but to abort one's child.</p>
        <p>Many countries in Central Europe, the Middle East, Africa and South America resent the arrogance of the United States in pushing this right, which in most cases is contrary to their laws and culture.</p>
        <p>ELSIE P. PALMER  Wayne, N.J., May 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
